<paragraph id="8BC07C19FFC0330BFF4EFAE6FAC6B805" blockId="10.[151,1437,1320,1866]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">
The subfamily characters are re-defined below on the basis of its three presently constituent genera, namely, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFF4EFA9EFEFCB806" authorityName="Southern" authorityYear="1921" box="[151,304,1360,1385]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Ficopomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFF4EFA9EFEFCB806" box="[151,304,1360,1385]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Ficopomatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEE01E8FFC0330BFEEEFA9EFE35B805" author="Southern, R." box="[311,505,1360,1386]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" pagination="563 - 659" refId="ref10144" refString="Southern, R. (1921) Polychaeta of the Chilka Lake and also of fresh and brackish waters in other parts of India. Memoirs of the Indian Museum, 5, 563 - 659." type="journal article" year="1921">Southern (1921)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFDDCFA9EFC54B805" authority="Absolon &amp; Hrabe 1930" authorityName="Absolon &amp; Hrabe" authorityYear="1930" box="[517,920,1360,1386]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Marifugia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFDDCFA9EFDB0B806" box="[517,636,1360,1385]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Marifugia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEE01E8FFC0330BFD5AFA9EFC54B805" author="Absolon, K &amp; Hrabe, S." box="[643,920,1360,1386]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" pagination="249 - 264" refId="ref8842" refString="Absolon, K &amp; Hrabe, S. (1930) Ueinen neuen Susswasser Polychaeten aus den Hohlengewassern der Herzegowina. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 88, 9 / 10, 249 - 264." type="journal article" year="1930">Absolon &amp; Hrabé 1930</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFC0CFA9EFACAB805" authority="Pillai (1960)" authorityName="Pillai" authorityYear="1960" box="[981,1286,1360,1386]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Neopomatus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFC0CFA9EFBABB806" box="[981,1127,1360,1385]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Neopomatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEE01E8FFC0330BFBB6FA9EFACAB805" author="Pillai, T. G." box="[1135,1286,1360,1386]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 40" refId="ref9930" refString="Pillai, T. G. (1960) Some Marine and Brackish-water Serpulid Polychaeta from Ceylon, including New Genera and Species. Ceylon Journal of Science (Biological Sciences), (3) 1, 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="1960">Pillai (1960)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC07C19FFC0330BFF1FFAB9FA9DBB5D" blockId="10.[151,1437,1320,1866]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFF1FFAB9FE1EB8FE" bold="true" box="[198,466,1399,1425]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Subfamily characters</emphasis>
: Operculum present, chitinous, occurring in position of first left branchial radiole; peduncle lacks pinnules and wings. Interradiolar membranes absent Number of thoracic chaetigers: 7 or 6; collar chaetae present or absent, strongly toothed when present; 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFC7FFA06FBD7B88E" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1844" box="[934,1051,1480,1505]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Apomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFC7FFA06FBD7B88E" box="[934,1051,1480,1505]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Apomatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-chaetae absent. Thoracic membranes free or joined over thorax; extend to end of thorax; apron present. Abdominal neurochaetae: geniculate. Anterior process of uncini gouged. Typical habitat: non-marine, i.e., brackish to totally freshwater.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3652F92FFC0330BFF1FF9F1FC4FBA25" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC07C19FFC0330BFF1FF9F1FC4FBA25" blockId="10.[151,1437,1320,1866]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFF1FF9F1FEF4BB36" bold="true" box="[198,312,1599,1625]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Remarks</emphasis>
: Most serpulimorph polychaetes occur in typically marine habitats. The ability to survive and reproduce in non-marine environments, ranging from hypersaline to brackish-water as, for example, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFA5FF9A6FEE9BBC6" baseAuthorityName="Fauvel" baseAuthorityYear="1923" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Ficopomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="enigmaticus">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFA5FF9A6FEE9BBC6" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">F. enigmaticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or brackish-water as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFD94F95EFD2ABBC6" authorityName="Pillai" authorityYear="1960" box="[589,742,1680,1705]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Neopomatus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="uschakovi">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFD94F95EFD2ABBC6" box="[589,742,1680,1705]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">N. uschakovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or even totally freshwater as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F079AFFC0330BFBA8F95EFA9FBBC6" authorityName="Absolon &amp; Hrabe" authorityYear="1930" box="[1137,1363,1680,1705]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Marifugia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="cavatica">
<emphasis id="B90BA00BFFC0330BFBA8F95EFA9FBBC6" box="[1137,1363,1680,1705]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="46">Marifugia cavatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is an important character that needs to be to be taken into consideration in view of physiological adaptations involved. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEE01E8FFC0330BFED4F92EFDDCBB95" author="Hennig, W." box="[269,528,1760,1786]" pageId="10" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 262" refId="ref9249" refString="Hennig, W. (1966) Phylogenetic systematics, Translated by D. Dwight Davis and Rainer Zangerl, University of Illinois Press, 1 - 262." type="book chapter" year="1966">Hennig (1966 p. 101)</bibRefCitation>
, while discussing the holomorphological methods of phylogenetic systematics, states that ‘it is an old demand that systematic work should consider “all characters as far as possible, and not be limited to only one sector of the fabric of characters.…..’
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
